SIMPLE: interruption
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interruption
<hw>In`ter*rup"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>interruptio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>interruption</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of interrupting, or breaking in
upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being interrupted; a breach or break,
caused by the abrupt intervention of something foreign; intervention;
interposition.</def> <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest the <qex>interruption</qex> of time cause you to lose the
idea of one part.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Obstruction caused by breaking in upon course,
current, progress, or motion; stop; hindrance; <as>as, the author has
met with many <ex>interruptions</ex> in the execution of his work; the
speaker or the argument proceeds without
<ex>interruption</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Temporary cessation; intermission;
suspension.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interruptive</ent>⟦br⟧
